This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it focuses on representation learning using deep models. The paper specifically discusses the use of deep features and their limitations when the distribution of data is different from the benchmark data set. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of cs.CV (Computer Vision) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as these fields heavily rely on deep learning and representation learning. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of Wasserstein ambiguity set constraints, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-categories of cs.CL (Computation and Language) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as these fields often use optimization techniques.
